< /p > < p > The "imitation game" ( OreVar interpretation of the 1950 < a OreVar = "/wiki/Turing_test" OreVar = "Turing test" > Turing test < /a > that assesses whether a computer can imitate a human ) is nowadays considered too exploitable to be a meaningful benchmark. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-285" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-285" > &#91 ; 274&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > A derivative of the Turing test is the Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart ( OreVar a OreVar = "/wiki/CAPTCHA" OreVar = "CAPTCHA" > CAPTCHA < /a > ) . As the name implies , this helps to determine that a user is an actual person and not a computer posing as a human. In contrast to the standard Turing test , CAPTCHA is administered by a machine and targeted to a human as opposed to being administered by a human and targeted to a machine. A computer asks a user to complete a simple test then generates a grade for that test. Computers are unable to solve the problem , so correct solutions are deemed to be the result of a person taking the test. A common type of CAPTCHA is the test that requires the typing of distorted letters , numbers or symbols that appear in an image undecipherable by a computer. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEO&#39 ; BrienMarakas2011_286-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEO&#39 ; BrienMarakas2011-286" > &#91 ; 275&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

This question is closely related to the philosophical problem as to the nature of human consciousness , generally referred to as the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Hard_problem_of_consciousness" OreVar = "Hard problem of consciousness" > hard problem of consciousness < /a > .

< p > In video games , artificial intelligence is routinely used to generate dynamic purposeful behavior in < a OreVar = "/wiki/Non-player_character" OreVar = "Non-player character" > non-player characters < /a > ( OreVar ) . In addition , well-understood AI techniques are routinely used for < a OreVar = "/wiki/Pathfinding" OreVar = "Pathfinding" > pathfinding < /a > . Some researchers consider NPC AI in games to be a "solved problem" for most production tasks. Games with more atypical AI include the AI director of < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Left_4_Dead" OreVar = "Left 4 Dead" > Left 4 Dead < /a > < /i > ( OreVar ) and the neuroevolutionary training of platoons in < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Supreme_Commander_2" OreVar = "Supreme Commander 2" > Supreme Commander 2 < /a > < /i > ( OreVar ) . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-329" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-329" > &#91 ; 318&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-330" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-330" > &#91 ; 319&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > Currently , 50+ countries are researching battlefield robots , including the United States , China , Russia , and the United Kingdom. Many people concerned about risk from superintelligent AI also want to limit the use of artificial soldiers and drones. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-390" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-390" > &#91 ; 379&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > In the early 1980s , AI research was revived by the commercial success of < a OreVar = "/wiki/Expert_system" OreVar = "Expert system" > expert systems < /a > , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Expert_systems_41-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Expert_systems-41" > &#91 ; 41&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > a form of AI program that simulated the knowledge and analytical skills of human experts. By 1985 , the market for AI had reached over a billion dollars. At the same time , Japan's < a OreVar = "/wiki/Fifth_generation_computer" OreVar = "Fifth generation computer" > fifth generation computer < /a > project inspired the U.S and British governments to restore funding for < a OreVar = "/wiki/Academic_research" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Academic research" > academic research < /a > . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-AI_in_the_80s_10-2" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-AI_in_the_80s-10" > &#91 ; 10&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > However , beginning with the collapse of the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Lisp_Machine" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Lisp Machine" > Lisp Machine < /a > market in 1987 , AI once again fell into disrepute , and a second , longer-lasting hiatus began. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Second_AI_winter_12-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Second_AI_winter-12" > &#91 ; 12&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > The earliest ( OreVar easiest to understand ) approach to AI was symbolism ( OreVar as formal logic ) : "If an otherwise healthy adult has a fever , then they may have < a OreVar = "/wiki/Influenza" OreVar = "Influenza" > influenza < /a > ". A second , more general , approach is < a OreVar = "/wiki/Bayesian_inference" OreVar = "Bayesian inference" > Bayesian inference < /a > : "If the current patient has a fever , adjust the probability they have influenza in such-and-such way". The third major approach , extremely popular in routine business AI applications , are analogizers such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Support_vector_machine" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Support vector machine" > SVM < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/K-nearest_neighbor_algorithm" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "K-nearest neighbor algorithm" > nearest-neighbor < /a > : "After examining the records of known past patients whose temperature , symptoms , age , and other factors mostly match the current patient , X% of those patients turned out to have influenza". A fourth approach is harder to intuitively understand , but is inspired by how the brain's machinery works: the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" OreVar = "Artificial neural network" > artificial neural network < /a > approach uses artificial " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Neurons" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Neurons" > neurons < /a > " that can learn by comparing itself to the desired output and altering the strengths of the connections between its internal neurons to "reinforce" connections that seemed to be useful. These four main approaches can overlap with each other and with evolutionary systems ; for example , neural nets can learn to make inferences , to generalize , and to make analogies. Some systems implicitly or explicitly use multiple of these approaches , alongside many other AI and non-AI algorithms ; the best approach is often different depending on the problem. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2 , _Chapter_4 , _Chapter_6_71-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2 , _Chapter_4 , _Chapter_6-71" > &#91 ; 69&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-72" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-72" > &#91 ; 70&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > Compared with humans , existing AI lacks several features of human " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Commonsense_reasoning" OreVar = "Commonsense reasoning" > commonsense reasoning < /a > " ; most notably , humans have powerful mechanisms for reasoning about " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Na%C3%AFve_physics" OreVar = "Naïve physics" > naïve physics < /a > " s" < a OreVar = "/wiki/Folk_psychology" OreVar = "Folk psychology" > folk psychology < /a > " that helps them to interpret natural-language sentences such as "The city councilmen refused the demonstrators a permit because they advocated violence". ( OreVar generic AI has difficulty discerning whether the ones alleged to be advocating violence are the councilmen or the demonstrators. ) < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-81" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-81" > &#91 ; 78&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-82" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-82" > &#91 ; 79&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-83" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-83" > &#91 ; 80&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > This lack of "common knowledge" means that AI often makes different mistakes than humans make , in ways that can seem incomprehensible. For example , existing self-driving cars cannot reason about the location nor the intentions of pedestrians in the exact way that humans do , and instead must use non-human modes of reasoning to avoid accidents. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-84" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-84" > &#91 ; 81&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-85" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-85" > &#91 ; 82&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-86" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-86" > &#91 ; 83&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > For example , consider what happens when a person is shown a color swatch and identifies it , saying "it's red". The easy problem only requires understanding the machinery in the brain that makes it possible for a person to know that the color swatch is red. The hard problem is that people also know something else—they also know < i > what red looks like < /i > . ( OreVar that a person born blind can know that something is red without knowing what red looks like. ) < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-402" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-402" > &#91 ; l&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Everyone knows subjective experience exists , because they do it every day ( OreVar , all sighted people know what red looks like ) . The hard problem is explaining how the brain creates it , why it exists , and how it is different from knowledge and other aspects of the brain.

Another study was reported to have found that artificial intelligence was as good as trained doctors in identifying skin cancers. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-302" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-302" > &#91 ; 291&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Another study is using artificial intelligence to try to monitor multiple high-risk patients , and this is done by asking each patient numerous questions based on data acquired from live doctor to patient interactions. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-303" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-303" > &#91 ; 292&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > One study was done with transfer learning , the machine performed a diagnosis similarly to a well-trained ophthalmologist , and could generate a decision within 30 seconds on whether or not the patient should be referred for treatment , with more than 95% accuracy. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-304" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-304" > &#91 ; 293&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >
